Methods to Add Elements in the DOM

document.createElement() → Create a new element.

appendChild() → Add element as the last child.

append() → Similar to appendChild() but can also insert text.

prepend() → Add element at the beginning.

insertBefore() → Insert before a specific node.

innerHTML → Insert HTML directly (less safe if user input).

Example 1: Append a new element
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Add Element Example</title>
</head>
<body>
  <div id="container">
    <h2>Student List</h2>
    <ul id="students">
      <li>Abhishek</li>
      <li>Rohit</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <script>
    // 1. Create a new element
    let newStudent = document.createElement("li");

    // 2. Add text to it
    newStudent.textContent = "Neha";

    // 3. Append to the list
    document.getElementById("students").appendChild(newStudent);
  </script>
</body>
</html>


Output:

Abhishek  
Rohit  
Neha

Example 2: Prepend an element
let firstStudent = document.createElement("li");
firstStudent.textContent = "First Student";
document.getElementById("students").prepend(firstStudent);


Adds "First Student" at the beginning of the list.

Example 3: Insert Before
let student = document.createElement("li");
student.textContent = "Inserted Before Rohit";

let list = document.getElementById("students");
let rohit = list.children[1]; // <li>Rohit</li>

list.insertBefore(student, rohit);

Example 4: Using innerHTML
document.getElementById("students").innerHTML += "<li>Kiran</li>";


Note: innerHTML re-renders the whole element → less efficient, potential XSS security issue if using user input.
